
As I have developed a clear understanding of AWS architecture, DevOps workflows, security best practices, and how to work in cloud-native services. I have applied these concepts in my Automation Tester role by designing and maintaining a production-grade CI/CD pipeline using GitLab, integrated with AWS services to automate regression and smoke testing. My CI/CD pipeline is also configured through .gitlab-ci.yml, where I designed several stages such as prepare, build, test, and deploy. Every job uses a specific Docker image ( maven:3.9-openjdk-17) defined using the image: keyword, enabling environment consistent across every executions. This eliminates local environment issues and ensures proper builds.To run jobs, I hosted GitLab Runners on EC2 instances using the Docker executor. These instances are part of an Auto Scaling Group (ASG) with lifecycle hooks managed by Lambda and CloudWatch Events for dynamic scaling based on CI load. I applied concepts like elasticity and decoupled architecture from the AWS course, which allowed the runners to scale up during peak testing windows and terminate gracefully post-job completion to optimize cost and performance. Our automated test cycles—both scheduled daily and event-triggered using GitLab’s only: [schedules, web] keyword—kicked off E2E tests with tools like Selenium, Postman. The test suites were built to be flexible, running across multiple environments with configurations managed via GitLab CI/CD variables and environment-specific files stored in S3.I have applied the IAM principles by giving the EC2 runners an instance profile with limited permissions to access S3, CloudWatch, and Secrets Manager. Secrets (API keys, DB credentials) are fetched at runtime via the AWS CLI and injected securely as environment variables inside the job context. This actually follows the principle of least privilege and adheres to best practices for secrets management — a topic of heavy focus in the CLF-C02 course. After testing, I have implemented logs and artifact management by uploading test reports, coverage results, screenshots to versioned S3 buckets. These artifacts are timestamped, categorized by GitLab pipeline ID, and used for debugging and reporting. I also used artifacts: and cache: in GitLab to optimize job execution time, reducing redundancy across jobs. I also implemented the Monitoring and observability using Amazon CloudWatch. I configured metric filters and dashboards to track test execution times, error rates, and instance health. Again, alarms are set for pipeline failures using SNS to notify relevant Slack channels and email groups. This aligns with the operational excellence pillar of the AWS Well-Architected Framework discussed in both courses. 
The impact of this implementation was substantial. It reduced manual regression efforts by 50%, increased deployment frequency by supporting automated test validation per environment push and ensured compliance with QA before production releases. This has empowered the testing team to shift-left and integrate testing earlier in the development lifecycle.
Challenges that I have encountered includes test flakiness due to inconsistent network latency and environment drift. I have planned to mitigate this by running isolated test environments using Docker Compose and pre-baked AMIs with all dependencies. Additionally, CloudWatch logs helped identify intermittent API timeout patterns, which were resolved via retries and better wait strategies in Selenium.
If I were rebuilding the project from scratch, I would have integrated AWS CodePipeline and CodeBuild to reduce the management overhead of EC2 runners and enhance native service integration. I would have also used Terraform for infrastructure-as-code to manage S3, IAM, and networking resources more consistently.

